WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:10.010 --> 00:00:11.890
[ Applause ]

00:00:11.890 --> 00:00:13.190
&gt;&gt; Karyn Temple: Good morning.

00:00:13.190 --> 00:00:15.540
Welcome to our 20th
copyright matters event.

00:00:15.540 --> 00:00:17.990
I am Karen Temple,
Acting Director

00:00:17.990 --> 00:00:20.050
of the United States
Copyright Office.

00:00:20.050 --> 00:00:21.490
Today we are excited

00:00:21.490 --> 00:00:25.210
to be celebrating the
lifecycle of copyright.

00:00:25.210 --> 00:00:27.800
What do I mean by the
lifecycle of copyright?

00:00:27.800 --> 00:00:31.830
Well generally, our friends at
Webster define the lifecycle

00:00:31.830 --> 00:00:34.840
as "the series of stages
through which something,

00:00:34.840 --> 00:00:37.080
such as an individual, culture

00:00:37.080 --> 00:00:40.780
or manufactured product
passes during its lifetime."

00:00:40.780 --> 00:00:43.950
While copyright, of course,
is not a living organism,

00:00:43.950 --> 00:00:46.460
it too has a lifecycle
and passes

00:00:46.460 --> 00:00:48.630
through many stages over time.

00:00:48.630 --> 00:00:50.580
Starting from the
very beginning,

00:00:50.580 --> 00:00:54.070
when it's not even a copyright
yet, but simply an idea

00:00:54.070 --> 00:00:58.260
or thought that serves as
that seed for a later piece

00:00:58.260 --> 00:01:02.760
of artwork, that then grows into
a fully formed copyrighted work,

00:01:02.760 --> 00:01:06.160
such as a book, song,
photograph or painting.

00:01:06.160 --> 00:01:08.520
Over the course of its lifecycle

00:01:08.520 --> 00:01:12.700
that copyrighted work may
spread far and wide on its own

00:01:12.700 --> 00:01:15.820
as it adapts and
generates other works.

00:01:15.820 --> 00:01:18.720
And finally, at the end of
its copyright lifecycle,

00:01:18.720 --> 00:01:22.120
when the full copyright term of
protection has been achieved,

00:01:22.120 --> 00:01:26.090
the copyright work returns
figuratively to the earth,

00:01:26.090 --> 00:01:29.530
as it enters the public
domain and is free to use

00:01:29.530 --> 00:01:30.830
and reuse by everyone.

00:01:30.830 --> 00:01:34.110
I still find it amazing
and inspiring

00:01:34.110 --> 00:01:35.940
that the founding
fathers were able

00:01:35.940 --> 00:01:39.290
to appreciate the extraordinary
importance of copyright

00:01:39.290 --> 00:01:42.590
and the copyright lifecycle
by enshrining it article one

00:01:42.590 --> 00:01:45.740
of our constitution insuring
both strong copyright

00:01:45.740 --> 00:01:49.790
protection, but also recognizing
the value of limited terms

00:01:49.790 --> 00:01:51.420
and the public domain.

00:01:51.420 --> 00:01:52.730
The full value and beauty

00:01:52.730 --> 00:01:55.460
of our copyright system can
unfortunately sometimes be

00:01:55.460 --> 00:01:58.560
forgotten and seen as
some sort of barrier

00:01:58.560 --> 00:01:59.930
to creation and innovation.

00:01:59.930 --> 00:02:02.680
When, in fact, it
is far from that.

00:02:02.680 --> 00:02:04.810
As the Supreme Court
has recognized,

00:02:04.810 --> 00:02:07.940
copyright is the engine
of free expression.

00:02:07.940 --> 00:02:11.730
And the lifecycle of copyright
including its exceptions,

00:02:11.730 --> 00:02:15.310
limited term and the
public domain is all part

00:02:15.310 --> 00:02:17.990
of that critically
important framework created

00:02:17.990 --> 00:02:19.700
on our constitution.

00:02:19.700 --> 00:02:23.630
So today, we have the distinct
pleasure to celebrate part

00:02:23.630 --> 00:02:25.230
of that lifecycle in a way

00:02:25.230 --> 00:02:28.010
that we have not been
able to do for some time.

00:02:28.010 --> 00:02:31.980
On January 1 of this year,
hundreds of works that had been

00:02:31.980 --> 00:02:35.820
under copyright protection
entered into the public domain.

00:02:35.820 --> 00:02:39.030
These were works that
had been created in 1923.

00:02:39.030 --> 00:02:41.090
Many have been widely
recognizable

00:02:41.090 --> 00:02:44.880
for almost 100 years, songs
such as the Charleston,

00:02:44.880 --> 00:02:47.930
as you just heard and
yes we have No Bananas.

00:02:47.930 --> 00:02:51.330
Films just as Harold
Lloyd's Safety Last.

00:02:51.330 --> 00:02:53.870
Buster Keaton's, Our Hospitality

00:02:53.870 --> 00:02:56.310
and Charlie Chaplan's
The Pilgrim.

00:02:56.310 --> 00:03:01.680
Books, stories and essays by
the likes of PG - GK Chesterton,

00:03:01.680 --> 00:03:06.070
Anton Chekov, Agatha
Christie, Aldous Huxley,

00:03:06.070 --> 00:03:09.270
F. Scott Fitzgerald,
Rudyard Kipling,

00:03:09.270 --> 00:03:12.330
Sinclair Lewis and
P.G. Woodhouse.

00:03:12.330 --> 00:03:16.030
These works would have entered
the public domain in 1999,

00:03:16.030 --> 00:03:18.470
but then following the
lead of the European Union

00:03:18.470 --> 00:03:22.000
and to protect American
authors from inequity overseas,

00:03:22.000 --> 00:03:24.260
Congress extended
copyright protection

00:03:24.260 --> 00:03:26.750
in the United States
by 20 years.

00:03:26.750 --> 00:03:29.820
And so this year is the
first time in two decades

00:03:29.820 --> 00:03:34.020
that a large batch of older
works has simultaneously fallen

00:03:34.020 --> 00:03:37.720
into the public domain
at one time.

00:03:37.720 --> 00:03:39.490
It is important to recognize

00:03:39.490 --> 00:03:42.130
that when a work enters the
public domain of course,

00:03:42.130 --> 00:03:45.940
it does not represent the death
of copyright; rather it is part

00:03:45.940 --> 00:03:47.730
of copyright's lifecycle.

00:03:47.730 --> 00:03:50.900
The next stage of life
for that creative work.

00:03:50.900 --> 00:03:53.670
The public domain is an
inherent and integral part

00:03:53.670 --> 00:03:55.240
of the copyright system.

00:03:55.240 --> 00:03:58.010
So, when people say that
they value copyright law,

00:03:58.010 --> 00:04:01.210
the public domain is a
crucial component of that.

00:04:01.210 --> 00:04:05.270
In fact, throughout our history
artistic hits have been often

00:04:05.270 --> 00:04:08.630
adaptations of classics that
were in the public domain

00:04:08.630 --> 00:04:12.110
or new creations called
from public domain sources.

00:04:12.110 --> 00:04:14.480
Hollywood films, Kiss Me Kate

00:04:14.480 --> 00:04:18.460
and more recently 10 Things I
Hate About You are adaptations

00:04:18.460 --> 00:04:20.880
of Shakespeare's
Taming of the Shrew.

00:04:20.880 --> 00:04:24.650
The 2009 novel and movie
Pride and Prejudice

00:04:24.650 --> 00:04:29.710
and Zombie's is an adaptation
of Jane Austen's classic novel

00:04:29.710 --> 00:04:33.590
and Beyonce's Ave Maria is
an adaptation of Schubert's.

00:04:33.590 --> 00:04:36.360
In fact, many popular
animated movies

00:04:36.360 --> 00:04:38.600
and theater productions
are modern

00:04:38.600 --> 00:04:40.880
and commercially
successful takes

00:04:40.880 --> 00:04:43.340
on classic public
domain fairy tales.

00:04:43.340 --> 00:04:46.960
Snow White and the Seven
Dwarfs, Cinderella,

00:04:46.960 --> 00:04:49.820
Sleeping Beauty,
Beauty and the Beast.

00:04:49.820 --> 00:04:54.430
This lifecycle of copyright is
crucial to the overall system.

00:04:54.430 --> 00:04:58.160
It provides authors the
inspiration and raw material

00:04:58.160 --> 00:04:59.460
to create something new.

00:04:59.460 --> 00:05:04.630
And that is why it is valued
by both authors and users,

00:05:04.630 --> 00:05:06.290
because often when it comes

00:05:06.290 --> 00:05:08.820
to the public domain
authors are users

00:05:08.820 --> 00:05:11.470
and users are authors
of copyrighted works.

00:05:11.470 --> 00:05:14.420
And that's why today we
are celebrating it here

00:05:14.420 --> 00:05:17.020
at the United States
Copyright Office.

00:05:17.020 --> 00:05:20.090
With that I would like to
invite up Whitney Levandusky,

00:05:20.090 --> 00:05:22.920
an attorney with the Office of
Public Information and Education

00:05:22.920 --> 00:05:24.470
at the Copyright Office.

00:05:24.470 --> 00:05:25.770
Whitney will talk a bit more

00:05:25.770 --> 00:05:28.950
about the public domains
importance and how it functions.

00:05:28.950 --> 00:05:32.260
She'll also introduce our
esteemed speakers for today.

00:05:32.260 --> 00:05:34.290
So with that, I will
turn it over to Whitney.

00:05:34.290 --> 00:05:36.090
Thank you.

00:05:36.090 --> 00:05:44.590
[ Applause ]

00:05:44.590 --> 00:05:45.890
&gt;&gt; Whitney Levandusky:
Thank you.

00:05:45.890 --> 00:05:48.380
As we heard from Acting
Register Karyn Temple,

00:05:48.380 --> 00:05:51.450
we're here to celebrate the
public domain, the next stage

00:05:51.450 --> 00:05:52.960
of life for a creative work.

00:05:52.960 --> 00:05:56.880
The Constitution allowed
Congress to grant copyright,

00:05:56.880 --> 00:05:59.880
but it also set forth
that the protection was

00:05:59.880 --> 00:06:01.580
for a limited time.

00:06:01.580 --> 00:06:03.480
This limited nature is important

00:06:03.480 --> 00:06:06.080
to the creative life
of the United States.

00:06:06.080 --> 00:06:09.730
Today, you will learn
about the many angles

00:06:09.730 --> 00:06:11.400
of the public domain.

00:06:11.400 --> 00:06:13.840
How does it work
for creative people?

00:06:13.840 --> 00:06:15.140
How can it work for each of us?

00:06:15.140 --> 00:06:17.980
And where can we find it?

00:06:17.980 --> 00:06:21.580
We'll learn about how public
domain works provide an ongoing

00:06:21.580 --> 00:06:24.620
and renewable legacy
of creativity.

00:06:24.620 --> 00:06:28.310
We'll hear from a documentarian
and a musical historian

00:06:28.310 --> 00:06:32.720
about how the public domain
assists and shapes their work.

00:06:32.720 --> 00:06:34.660
We will also explore
this rich background

00:06:34.660 --> 00:06:37.150
and highlight some works
and authors of those works

00:06:37.150 --> 00:06:39.820
that are entering the
public domain this year.

00:06:39.820 --> 00:06:45.230
So, the public domain,
it's not a place.

00:06:45.230 --> 00:06:47.240
We can't find it on a map.

00:06:47.240 --> 00:06:50.020
When we say public
domain, we mean simply

00:06:50.020 --> 00:06:52.250
that the work is not
protected by copyright

00:06:52.250 --> 00:06:55.120
and it's free for anyone to use.

00:06:55.120 --> 00:06:58.720
The public domain is a
wellspring of knowledge

00:06:58.720 --> 00:07:02.930
and creativity that allows
individuals at institutions

00:07:02.930 --> 00:07:06.660
to supply new creativity
and thought.

00:07:06.660 --> 00:07:08.960
Vampires -

00:07:12.170 --> 00:07:15.460
Pride and Prejudice.

00:07:15.460 --> 00:07:18.810
The works of Jules
Verne and H.G. Wells.

00:07:18.810 --> 00:07:21.260
These are just a
few brief examples

00:07:21.260 --> 00:07:23.630
about how we've used
the public domain

00:07:23.630 --> 00:07:26.560
to inspire new creative works.

00:07:26.560 --> 00:07:28.860
The public domain
gives us the ability

00:07:28.860 --> 00:07:32.640
to stretch our imaginations,
to take common touchstones

00:07:32.640 --> 00:07:37.230
to new places, and
re-evaluate long-standing works

00:07:37.230 --> 00:07:40.120
in contemporary times.

00:07:40.120 --> 00:07:43.100
While we are highlighting
today the end of copyright term

00:07:43.100 --> 00:07:46.210
as one way of growing the
public domain, Karyn mentioned

00:07:46.210 --> 00:07:48.980
that the public domain
is far more than works

00:07:48.980 --> 00:07:51.450
who copyright term has ended.

00:07:51.450 --> 00:07:53.980
There are a number of other
ways that work - that works are

00:07:53.980 --> 00:07:55.590
in the public domain
from their inception.

00:07:55.590 --> 00:07:59.940
All works, for example
created by federal employees

00:07:59.940 --> 00:08:03.250
in the scope of their employment
are in the public domain.

00:08:03.250 --> 00:08:06.470
A small sampling of works
created by employees

00:08:06.470 --> 00:08:09.740
in the public trust
include the fruits

00:08:09.740 --> 00:08:12.930
of the works progress
administration.

00:08:12.930 --> 00:08:14.590
The first photograph of earth

00:08:14.590 --> 00:08:19.730
by astronaut Bill
Anders, titled Earth Rise.

00:08:19.730 --> 00:08:24.130
Photographs from field work
by government agencies.

00:08:24.130 --> 00:08:26.430
Medical imageries -

00:08:29.410 --> 00:08:31.910
Medical imagery, there we go.

00:08:31.910 --> 00:08:35.320
And of course, studies
and reports produced

00:08:35.320 --> 00:08:38.740
by the government including
the copyright office.

00:08:38.740 --> 00:08:41.420
And oftentimes we
use the public domain

00:08:41.420 --> 00:08:44.080
to extend beyond creative works.

00:08:44.080 --> 00:08:46.890
We use public domain to
refer to the building blocks

00:08:46.890 --> 00:08:48.530
of knowledge and creativity.

00:08:48.530 --> 00:08:54.070
Things like facts, processes
and systems, basic shapes,

00:08:54.070 --> 00:08:57.560
social dances, short
words and phrases.

00:08:57.560 --> 00:09:01.040
All in all, the public domain
is the wealth of resources

00:09:01.040 --> 00:09:04.650
that are available to everyone.

00:09:04.650 --> 00:09:08.350
Now there may be no more
immediate example of inspiration

00:09:08.350 --> 00:09:12.320
of public domain works than
those penned by Shakespeare.

00:09:12.320 --> 00:09:14.840
The Folger Shakespeare Library,
which is just across the street

00:09:14.840 --> 00:09:18.770
from us, it has the largest
collection of materials relating

00:09:18.770 --> 00:09:21.950
to Shakespeare and his works,
which includes centuries

00:09:21.950 --> 00:09:27.890
of adaptations on the stage,
in music, in art and for film.

00:09:27.890 --> 00:09:29.760
We will be using
the long history

00:09:29.760 --> 00:09:33.090
of Shakespearian
inspiration as the focal point

00:09:33.090 --> 00:09:34.930
to examine the important role

00:09:34.930 --> 00:09:37.770
of public domain
works and adaptation.

00:09:37.770 --> 00:09:40.740
Our first presenter
is Douglas Lanier.

00:09:40.740 --> 00:09:43.920
He is the Professor of English
at University of New Hampshire,

00:09:43.920 --> 00:09:45.910
and a long term research fellow

00:09:45.910 --> 00:09:47.850
at the Folger Shakespeare
Library.

00:09:47.850 --> 00:09:52.110
He did is graduate work at Duke
University, and he specialized

00:09:52.110 --> 00:09:54.370
in medieval and early
modern drama.

00:09:54.370 --> 00:09:59.570
He has taught at Duke, UCLA,
Alleghany College, Gonville

00:09:59.570 --> 00:10:03.280
and Caius College, Cambridge,
the University of Milan

00:10:03.280 --> 00:10:06.430
and University de
Murcia in Spain.

00:10:06.430 --> 00:10:09.930
His pioneering work in the
study of modern adaptations

00:10:09.930 --> 00:10:13.790
of Shakespeare in mass media
will provide the foundation

00:10:13.790 --> 00:10:16.520
for his insight into the
cultural recirculation

00:10:16.520 --> 00:10:19.920
of public domain works,
the cultural after-life

00:10:19.920 --> 00:10:23.720
and the elevation of works
through adaptations over time.

00:10:23.720 --> 00:10:26.720
His book, Shakespeare and
Modern Popular Culture,

00:10:26.720 --> 00:10:28.930
established the basic
parameters of one

00:10:28.930 --> 00:10:31.090
of the five most
liveliest fields

00:10:31.090 --> 00:10:33.000
of Shakespeare studies today.

00:10:33.000 --> 00:10:36.340
He is currently at work
on two book projects.

00:10:36.340 --> 00:10:38.450
First, a history of
screen adaptation

00:10:38.450 --> 00:10:41.270
of an Othello worldwide,
and second a study

00:10:41.270 --> 00:10:44.010
of reparative Shakespeare,
which are productions

00:10:44.010 --> 00:10:45.960
of Shakespeare addressed
to the traumas

00:10:45.960 --> 00:10:48.110
of socially marginalized groups.

00:10:48.110 --> 00:10:52.510
So please welcome me - in
joining - in welcoming Douglas.

00:10:52.510 --> 00:11:01.890
[ Applause ]

00:11:01.890 --> 00:11:04.820
&gt;&gt; Douglas Lanier:
Hello, can you hear me?

00:11:04.820 --> 00:11:09.580
Of the original public - oops.

00:11:09.580 --> 00:11:11.250
There we go.

00:11:11.250 --> 00:11:14.760
The original public
domain materials

00:11:14.760 --> 00:11:18.930
in western culture are what
we've come to call the classics

00:11:18.930 --> 00:11:21.980
of Greek and Latin antiquity.

00:11:21.980 --> 00:11:26.150
They did not begin
their lives as classics.

00:11:26.150 --> 00:11:30.010
These works were freely
available for creative use,

00:11:30.010 --> 00:11:33.400
rhetoricians call imitation,

00:11:33.400 --> 00:11:37.180
by all who can master
the written languages.

00:11:37.180 --> 00:11:40.520
It was through their
recirculation and adapted form

00:11:40.520 --> 00:11:44.140
that they attained the
status of a classic.

00:11:44.140 --> 00:11:48.940
The word classic then specifies
not some monumental steady

00:11:48.940 --> 00:11:53.060
state, but the result
of an ongoing dynamic,

00:11:53.060 --> 00:11:55.800
always historically
contingent process.

00:11:55.800 --> 00:11:59.580
An important condition of
which is the works availability

00:11:59.580 --> 00:12:01.210
in the public realm.

00:12:01.210 --> 00:12:06.770
And this process of
classicizing involves a paradox.

00:12:06.770 --> 00:12:08.210
The cultural after-life

00:12:08.210 --> 00:12:15.640
of a work depends upon its being
creatively altered, repurposed,

00:12:15.640 --> 00:12:17.100
appropriated, made

00:12:17.100 --> 00:12:20.160
into something other
than its former self.

00:12:20.160 --> 00:12:24.640
A work is effectively dead
unless it has new readers

00:12:24.640 --> 00:12:29.280
and audiences, new performers
and adapters who allow it

00:12:29.280 --> 00:12:32.470
to speak to a new present.

00:12:32.470 --> 00:12:34.890
I'm going to dodge for the
moment some very tricky

00:12:34.890 --> 00:12:38.230
questions about politics
and ethics

00:12:38.230 --> 00:12:40.750
in this process of
appropriation.

00:12:40.750 --> 00:12:42.500
There's nothing to guarantee

00:12:42.500 --> 00:12:46.250
that adaptations will be
faithful to their sources

00:12:46.250 --> 00:12:47.870
and nothing to guarantee

00:12:47.870 --> 00:12:52.760
that adaptations will serve
socially responsible purposes.

00:12:52.760 --> 00:12:56.220
Here I want simply to
observe that a condition

00:12:56.220 --> 00:12:59.780
for art having a
robust after-life is

00:12:59.780 --> 00:13:05.610
that it is available
for creative adaptation.

00:13:05.610 --> 00:13:08.010
Now in the Anglophone
literary tradition,

00:13:08.010 --> 00:13:11.370
several artists have achieved
the status of classics;

00:13:11.370 --> 00:13:13.900
Jane Austen, Charlotte Bronte

00:13:13.900 --> 00:13:17.330
and Charles Dickens come
immediately to mind.

00:13:17.330 --> 00:13:23.220
But none has had a history of
adaptation as long, as varied,

00:13:23.220 --> 00:13:27.500
as global in scope
as Shakespeare.

00:13:27.500 --> 00:13:31.400
He is the Coca Cola
of literature.

00:13:32.950 --> 00:13:35.430
And through the - and
though the reasons

00:13:35.430 --> 00:13:39.120
for his extraordinary
cultural after-life are many,

00:13:39.120 --> 00:13:42.630
one key is that Shakespeare's
work has long been

00:13:42.630 --> 00:13:44.170
in the public domain.

00:13:44.170 --> 00:13:48.440
And therefore, an irresistible
object for adaptation.

00:13:48.440 --> 00:13:49.740
Now it's possible to think

00:13:49.740 --> 00:13:53.470
about Shakespearian
adaptation from several angles.

00:13:53.470 --> 00:13:56.980
One has to do with medium.

00:13:56.980 --> 00:14:00.650
Shakespeare's dramatic
writing needs to be converted

00:14:00.650 --> 00:14:05.730
from its initial form as a
script into a living performance

00:14:05.730 --> 00:14:09.290
for any of his works
to become a play.

00:14:09.290 --> 00:14:13.410
Interestingly, Shakespeare's
early cultural after-life

00:14:13.410 --> 00:14:15.040
involve his being presented

00:14:15.040 --> 00:14:19.000
in the public realm
in two forms at once.

00:14:19.000 --> 00:14:22.280
As a stage performance,
developing in a number

00:14:22.280 --> 00:14:25.820
of directions over the
18th and 19th century.

00:14:25.820 --> 00:14:30.930
And as a printed book, first
appearing as the first folio

00:14:30.930 --> 00:14:36.300
in 1623 the printed collection
that redefined Shakespeare

00:14:36.300 --> 00:14:41.140
as an object for readers
rather than theater audiences.

00:14:41.140 --> 00:14:47.820
Now this two-track mode of
adaptation, stage and print,

00:14:47.820 --> 00:14:49.870
the two predominant
literary modes

00:14:49.870 --> 00:14:52.870
of the period may
have much to do

00:14:52.870 --> 00:14:57.010
with Shakespeare's
status as a classic.

00:14:57.010 --> 00:15:01.150
As new media emerged
in cultural importance,

00:15:01.150 --> 00:15:05.720
so too did Shakespeare
become accommodated to them.

00:15:05.720 --> 00:15:08.980
The 19th century for
example was particularly keen

00:15:08.980 --> 00:15:14.820
to adapt Shakespeare to the
newly ascended form of opera

00:15:14.820 --> 00:15:17.230
and instrumental music.

00:15:17.230 --> 00:15:22.240
In the 20th century, here we go,

00:15:22.240 --> 00:15:25.720
Shakespeare's writings have
been adapted to all modes

00:15:25.720 --> 00:15:30.660
of new media, advertising
motion pictures, radio,

00:15:30.660 --> 00:15:37.160
audio performance, television,
digital text, even social media.

00:15:37.160 --> 00:15:39.490
In the central function

00:15:39.490 --> 00:15:42.100
of Shakespearian
adaptation has been

00:15:42.100 --> 00:15:48.070
to make new media formats seem
less intimidating and alien,

00:15:48.070 --> 00:15:52.920
to demonstrate their utility or
lend them cultural authority.

00:15:52.920 --> 00:15:55.440
This is particularly
true at moments

00:15:55.440 --> 00:15:57.380
where a new medium might seem

00:15:57.380 --> 00:16:01.210
to threaten the cultural
status quo; such was the case

00:16:01.210 --> 00:16:05.190
with silent Shakespeare films
in the early 20th century

00:16:05.190 --> 00:16:10.120
or radio Shakespeare in
the US in the mid-1930's.

00:16:10.120 --> 00:16:16.690
In a process we call reciprocal
legitimation Shakespeare serves

00:16:16.690 --> 00:16:19.120
to legitimize the new medium,

00:16:19.120 --> 00:16:21.990
while at the same time
the new medium serves

00:16:21.990 --> 00:16:25.410
to legitimize Shakespeare's
status as a classic

00:16:25.410 --> 00:16:27.340
and reconfirm his place

00:16:27.340 --> 00:16:30.210
in the public realm
for a new generation.

00:16:30.210 --> 00:16:32.050
Now I should stress that this -

00:16:32.050 --> 00:16:35.360
that each new media
manifestation

00:16:35.360 --> 00:16:40.100
of Shakespeare always involves
reconceiving what Shakespeare

00:16:40.100 --> 00:16:41.410
can be.

00:16:41.410 --> 00:16:44.820
It's never just a
matter of reformatting.

00:16:44.820 --> 00:16:47.090
Film Shakespeare
is very different

00:16:47.090 --> 00:16:50.430
from stage Shakespeare,
print Shakespeare,

00:16:50.430 --> 00:16:53.570
televisional Shakespeare,
radio Shakespeare.

00:16:53.570 --> 00:16:57.380
Each of these media
highlight certain elements

00:16:57.380 --> 00:17:01.140
of Shakespeare's art and
makes new perceptions

00:17:01.140 --> 00:17:03.810
of his achievement possible.

00:17:03.810 --> 00:17:07.470
We come to Shakespeare on film,
with different expectations

00:17:07.470 --> 00:17:10.770
of realism than we do
with print Shakespeare

00:17:10.770 --> 00:17:12.510
or stage Shakespeare.

00:17:12.510 --> 00:17:16.970
The actors work and technique
is different in film Shakespeare

00:17:16.970 --> 00:17:20.120
than it is in audio
or stage productions.

00:17:20.120 --> 00:17:24.370
And how we experience our
Shakespeare in the theater

00:17:24.370 --> 00:17:29.310
and home, on a large or
small screen, in live

00:17:29.310 --> 00:17:33.680
or recorded format effects
how we understand the nature

00:17:33.680 --> 00:17:36.670
and significance of
Shakespeare's art.

00:17:36.670 --> 00:17:39.850
A new media can get
us to think anew

00:17:39.850 --> 00:17:42.880
about Shakespeare's
own artistry.

00:17:42.880 --> 00:17:45.300
In the opening speech of Henry V

00:17:45.300 --> 00:17:49.730
for example the chorus
expresses his dissatisfaction

00:17:49.730 --> 00:17:53.060
with the stage apparatus
of the globe theater.

00:17:53.060 --> 00:17:58.860
The wooden O with small casques
and an unworthy scaffold,

00:17:58.860 --> 00:18:04.450
all that is inadequate to the
epic greatness of Henry Campaign

00:18:04.450 --> 00:18:07.660
in the vast fields of France.

00:18:07.660 --> 00:18:12.150
Is Shakespeare here imagining
the as yet, unborn medium

00:18:12.150 --> 00:18:15.650
of modern film with
its capacity to show

00:18:15.650 --> 00:18:20.100
in wide screen splendor what
Shakespeare can only ask his

00:18:20.100 --> 00:18:23.330
audience to imagine
in the mind's eye?

00:18:23.330 --> 00:18:27.810
In other words, does filming
Shakespeare's plays allow us

00:18:27.810 --> 00:18:32.860
to see qualities that
were there all along?

00:18:32.860 --> 00:18:36.250
Shakespeare's cultural
after-life is also dependent

00:18:36.250 --> 00:18:39.990
on our ability to change
the content of his work

00:18:39.990 --> 00:18:43.140
to suit the tenor
and taste of the time

00:18:43.140 --> 00:18:45.870
and the purposes of adaptors.

00:18:45.870 --> 00:18:48.810
Practically no stage production

00:18:48.810 --> 00:18:52.860
of Shakespeare performs
the text as written.

00:18:52.860 --> 00:18:57.620
18th and 19th century dramatis
routinely produced their own

00:18:57.620 --> 00:19:01.630
versions of the plays,
smoothing out the meter,

00:19:01.630 --> 00:19:04.980
adding new characters
and subplots,

00:19:04.980 --> 00:19:09.100
ruthlessly cutting what they
thought was obscure or body.

00:19:09.100 --> 00:19:13.200
Even crafting happy
endings or the tragedies

00:19:13.200 --> 00:19:18.770
as Name Tate famously did
for his 1681 King Lear,

00:19:18.770 --> 00:19:23.400
the text of which ruled the
stage for the next 150 years.

00:19:23.400 --> 00:19:26.340
Adaptors have filled in
the gaps in the lives

00:19:26.340 --> 00:19:29.860
of Shakespeare's characters
and of Shakespeare himself

00:19:29.860 --> 00:19:33.270
with fully fleshed out
fictional biographies,

00:19:33.270 --> 00:19:35.350
prequels and sequels.

00:19:35.350 --> 00:19:39.560
Some even inserting the
author into the mix.

00:19:39.560 --> 00:19:40.960
The film Shakespeare in Love

00:19:40.960 --> 00:19:44.260
for example continues
the long tradition

00:19:44.260 --> 00:19:48.310
of imagining what we can't get
from the historical record.

00:19:48.310 --> 00:19:51.600
The process by which
Shakespeare conceived

00:19:51.600 --> 00:19:54.630
and wrote Romeo and Juliet.

00:19:54.630 --> 00:19:59.500
Shakespeare's scripts are now
routinely recontextualized

00:19:59.500 --> 00:20:05.040
in all manners of settings,
from the Tempest in Outer Space

00:20:05.040 --> 00:20:09.330
to Macbeth in a mental hospital
to Midsummer Night's Dream

00:20:09.330 --> 00:20:14.580
in modern Hollywood to Othello
in a southern prep school.

00:20:14.580 --> 00:20:17.250
And film and television
have long dressed

00:20:17.250 --> 00:20:21.210
up Shakespeare's work in
modern dress and language,

00:20:21.210 --> 00:20:23.670
so that we're often
watching Shakespeare

00:20:23.670 --> 00:20:26.120
without knowing we're doing so.

00:20:26.120 --> 00:20:30.360
My students are often
surprised when I tell them

00:20:30.360 --> 00:20:34.820
that 10 Things I Hate About You
is an adaptation of the Taming

00:20:34.820 --> 00:20:39.740
of the Shrew, or the Zombie
romance Warm Bodies is a version

00:20:39.740 --> 00:20:42.300
of Romeo and Juliet.

00:20:42.300 --> 00:20:46.660
Indeed the increasingly
oral and visual nature

00:20:46.660 --> 00:20:48.960
of 21st century Shakespeare,

00:20:48.960 --> 00:20:52.860
that is to say it's
non-literary bent as well

00:20:52.860 --> 00:20:55.350
as the globalization
of Shakespeare,

00:20:55.350 --> 00:20:59.180
which is to say Shakespeare
in translation means

00:20:59.180 --> 00:21:02.460
that our Shakespeare
is much less centered

00:21:02.460 --> 00:21:06.150
on the specificities of
Shakespeare's language.

00:21:06.150 --> 00:21:12.010
The wildly popular interactive
performance piece Sleep No More,

00:21:12.010 --> 00:21:17.270
by the British Performance Troop
Punch Drunk uses Shakespeare's

00:21:17.270 --> 00:21:19.890
Macbeth as its inspiration.

00:21:19.890 --> 00:21:23.740
Not a word of Shakespeare's
script is ever uttered

00:21:23.740 --> 00:21:27.740
as the audience wanders through
the company's meticulously

00:21:27.740 --> 00:21:32.570
constructed environment and
watches the silent actors.

00:21:32.570 --> 00:21:35.770
Lastly, Shakespeare's
availability

00:21:35.770 --> 00:21:40.800
in the public realm becomes a
vehicle for cultural dialog.

00:21:40.800 --> 00:21:45.530
A shear terrain on which
ideas can do battle or speak

00:21:45.530 --> 00:21:47.860
across cultural divides.

00:21:47.860 --> 00:21:51.920
With Shakespeare adaptors
speak to the present

00:21:51.920 --> 00:21:56.030
through a well-established
common set of stories,

00:21:56.030 --> 00:22:01.150
and they can also talk back to
the past or protest injustice

00:22:01.150 --> 00:22:05.910
by co-opting Shakespeare's
inherited cultural authority.

00:22:05.910 --> 00:22:10.320
The Tempest has long been
recognized as a founding text

00:22:10.320 --> 00:22:13.480
in the discourse of
western colonialism.

00:22:13.480 --> 00:22:19.510
A work that asserts the need to
subjugate unruly native people's

00:22:19.510 --> 00:22:23.270
but through adaptation the
Tempest has become a powerful

00:22:23.270 --> 00:22:27.790
mean to contest colonial
discourse,

00:22:27.790 --> 00:22:33.480
to assert a perspective untold
in Shakespeare's original play.

00:22:33.480 --> 00:22:37.250
In Aime Cesaire's
adaptation Une Tempete,

00:22:37.250 --> 00:22:39.580
the rebellious Caliban proud

00:22:39.580 --> 00:22:44.220
of his African heritage
eventually abandons the old

00:22:44.220 --> 00:22:48.960
helpless prospero, gaining
in the process victory

00:22:48.960 --> 00:22:52.020
over his colonial tormentor.

00:22:52.020 --> 00:22:54.710
In Shylock is my Name,

00:22:54.710 --> 00:22:57.510
one of the recent Hogarth
Shakespeare series,

00:22:57.510 --> 00:23:01.670
a set of pros retellings
of Shakespeare's plays,

00:23:01.670 --> 00:23:06.410
Howard Jacobson depicts
and erasable Shylock

00:23:06.410 --> 00:23:10.850
who magically reappears
in contemporary Manchester

00:23:10.850 --> 00:23:15.070
to a modern lapsed
Jew named Strolovich,

00:23:15.070 --> 00:23:18.920
who is himself a
victim of anti-Semitism.

00:23:18.920 --> 00:23:22.730
In the novel, Shylock
uses the situation

00:23:22.730 --> 00:23:27.380
to answer Shakespeare's
anti-Semitic portrayal of him

00:23:27.380 --> 00:23:29.480
in the Merchant of Venice.

00:23:29.480 --> 00:23:33.580
He engineers a way to replay
the famous trial scene

00:23:33.580 --> 00:23:37.310
on his own comic
terms, so that both he

00:23:37.310 --> 00:23:40.270
and Strolovich are redeemed.

00:23:40.270 --> 00:23:45.100
The contemporary Indian
filmmaker Vishal Bhardwaj,

00:23:45.100 --> 00:23:49.530
has made a trio of films that
reimagined Indian culture,

00:23:49.530 --> 00:23:55.310
I'm thinking of the films
Maqbool, Omkara and Haider.

00:23:55.310 --> 00:23:59.740
He uses his Shakespeare
to comment on live issues

00:23:59.740 --> 00:24:03.890
in Indian society, matters
like organized crime

00:24:03.890 --> 00:24:08.160
and civic corruption, the
persistence of the caste system,

00:24:08.160 --> 00:24:10.980
honor killing and terrorism.

00:24:10.980 --> 00:24:14.320
The work of Bhardwaj
and other contemporary,

00:24:14.320 --> 00:24:17.190
non-Anglophone adaptors suggest

00:24:17.190 --> 00:24:21.620
that Shakespeare is becoming
a global Lingua Franca,

00:24:21.620 --> 00:24:23.670
a set of plots, characters,

00:24:23.670 --> 00:24:29.960
motifs and themes sufficiently
familiar worldwide to open

00:24:29.960 --> 00:24:34.730
up new possibilities of
cross-cultural storytelling.

00:24:34.730 --> 00:24:39.120
Let me end on two points,
first the relationship

00:24:39.120 --> 00:24:42.540
between cultural
after-lives and adaptation

00:24:42.540 --> 00:24:46.720
that I'm discussing is
not unique to Shakespeare.

00:24:46.720 --> 00:24:52.300
He illustrates well the paradox
of art in the public realm.

00:24:52.300 --> 00:24:59.670
That artworks robust cultural
after-life depends upon its

00:24:59.670 --> 00:25:04.640
being taken up and manipulated
by later generations.

00:25:04.640 --> 00:25:07.670
Not all of whom will be
faithful to the original

00:25:07.670 --> 00:25:11.220
or respectful of its intentions.

00:25:11.220 --> 00:25:17.310
Cultural after-lives depend
upon creative infidelity.

00:25:17.310 --> 00:25:22.640
My second point is that if one
takes the long historical view

00:25:22.640 --> 00:25:26.520
adaptation has long
been the cultural norm

00:25:26.520 --> 00:25:28.930
in creative communities.

00:25:28.930 --> 00:25:32.540
The notion that authors
can exercise control

00:25:32.540 --> 00:25:36.530
of after their works have
entered the public arena is a

00:25:36.530 --> 00:25:40.990
relatively new and
culturally specific notion,

00:25:40.990 --> 00:25:45.160
modern copyright
dates from 1709.

00:25:45.160 --> 00:25:48.970
And perhaps it's a historical
aberration challenged

00:25:48.970 --> 00:25:53.720
by the creative impulse
to sample a new technology

00:25:53.720 --> 00:25:57.390
that makes that especially
easy to do.

00:25:57.390 --> 00:26:02.280
How to sustain current concepts
of copyright in the face

00:26:02.280 --> 00:26:05.460
of contemporary adaptational
practice seems

00:26:05.460 --> 00:26:07.460
to me a question worth asking.

00:26:07.460 --> 00:26:09.260
Thank you.

00:26:09.260 --> 00:26:24.040
[ Applause ]

00:26:24.040 --> 00:26:25.340
&gt;&gt; Whitney Levandusky:
Thank you Doug.

00:26:25.340 --> 00:26:28.320
So we know that the works of
Shakespeare were never protected

00:26:28.320 --> 00:26:30.440
under US copyright law.

00:26:30.440 --> 00:26:33.680
But, what if all
these adaptations

00:26:33.680 --> 00:26:36.150
if they were protected
under copyright,

00:26:36.150 --> 00:26:38.680
how long does protection last?

00:26:38.680 --> 00:26:41.670
Duration of copyright
looks a lot different today

00:26:41.670 --> 00:26:43.220
than it did in 1923.

00:26:43.220 --> 00:26:48.060
For works created today, the
general rule is that duration

00:26:48.060 --> 00:26:51.720
of copyright is life of
the author plus 70 years.

00:26:51.720 --> 00:26:56.360
The works that expired on
January 1, 2019 protect -

00:26:56.360 --> 00:26:58.570
were protected under
an original term

00:26:58.570 --> 00:27:02.280
of 26 years and a renewal term.

00:27:02.280 --> 00:27:05.650
The original term was secured
by publication with notice,

00:27:05.650 --> 00:27:08.590
or registration with
the US Copyright Office.

00:27:08.590 --> 00:27:12.060
The renewal term was
secured only by registration

00:27:12.060 --> 00:27:14.130
with the Copyright Office.

00:27:14.130 --> 00:27:17.170
This renewal term, it
was originally 26 years,

00:27:17.170 --> 00:27:19.430
but through a series
of acts by Congress,

00:27:19.430 --> 00:27:23.650
the last one being the Sonny
Bono Copyright Term Extension

00:27:23.650 --> 00:27:28.860
Act, eventually the renewal
term was extended to 69 years.

00:27:28.860 --> 00:27:30.580
This - Congresses ability

00:27:30.580 --> 00:27:34.260
to pass these extensions was
affirmed by the Supreme Court

00:27:34.260 --> 00:27:36.900
in Eldridge vs. Ashcroft.

00:27:36.900 --> 00:27:40.340
As a result, these works
first publisher registered

00:27:40.340 --> 00:27:44.490
in 1923 secured a
copyright term of 95 years.

00:27:44.490 --> 00:27:47.800
This term structure,
an original term

00:27:47.800 --> 00:27:50.360
and a renewal term
governs all works

00:27:50.360 --> 00:27:55.070
that first secured protection
prior to January 1, 1978.

00:27:55.070 --> 00:27:57.050
There are many technical
rules with duration

00:27:57.050 --> 00:27:58.800
that I won't belabor today.

00:27:58.800 --> 00:28:01.840
But know this, we
will see a new crop

00:28:01.840 --> 00:28:04.750
of works enter the
public domain each year.

00:28:04.750 --> 00:28:07.820
For example, works from 1924
will enter the public domain

00:28:07.820 --> 00:28:09.120
in 2020.

00:28:09.120 --> 00:28:13.310
1925, 2021 and so on.

00:28:13.310 --> 00:28:19.070
The use of public domain images
and footage helps us - oops,

00:28:19.070 --> 00:28:21.040
helps us to build
our sense of history.

00:28:21.040 --> 00:28:23.990
They provide context to
first person narratives.

00:28:23.990 --> 00:28:28.440
An artist can claim -
recast public domain works

00:28:28.440 --> 00:28:31.590
to deepen our connections
to the past.

00:28:31.590 --> 00:28:34.580
For example, Peter
Jackson's recent documentary,

00:28:34.580 --> 00:28:37.850
They Shall Not Grow Old
modified original footage

00:28:37.850 --> 00:28:40.690
from World War I
with colorization,

00:28:40.690 --> 00:28:44.740
modern production techniques,
sound effects and voice acting.

00:28:44.740 --> 00:28:48.430
In this clip courtesy of
the Imperial War Museum,

00:28:48.430 --> 00:28:49.780
Jackson provides insight

00:28:49.780 --> 00:28:52.440
into the thought process
behind their interpretation

00:28:52.440 --> 00:28:54.320
of public domain footage.

