&gt;&gt; Nina Gilden Seavey:
Thank you.

00:31:15.050 --> 00:31:18.140
Well I'm not as famous
as Peter Jackson,

00:31:18.140 --> 00:31:20.890
but he and I share
the same problems

00:31:20.890 --> 00:31:24.320
of how do you create
something out of the past?

00:31:24.320 --> 00:31:29.980
Now in his World War I film
he used public domain images

00:31:29.980 --> 00:31:31.700
as archival material.

00:31:31.700 --> 00:31:35.680
I mean it was literally
artifact of a certain era,

00:31:35.680 --> 00:31:39.030
about which he was making
a very literal film.

00:31:39.030 --> 00:31:42.390
Most documentary filmmakers
are not doing that.

00:31:42.390 --> 00:31:47.410
We're taking images that we
need to represent a story

00:31:47.410 --> 00:31:51.590
that we are shaping into an
entirely different narrative.

00:31:51.590 --> 00:31:54.730
So we're not using these
images as artifact,

00:31:54.730 --> 00:31:57.610
but we're using them
as representation.

00:31:57.610 --> 00:31:59.940
So I - because I am
a professor I'm going

00:31:59.940 --> 00:32:01.680
to give you a little assignment.

00:32:01.680 --> 00:32:05.610
I am going to show
you a clip from a film

00:32:05.610 --> 00:32:09.310
