my film A Paralyzing Fear

00:32:09.310 --> 00:32:12.220
of the Story of Polio
in America.

00:32:12.220 --> 00:32:17.730
And this film posed a number
of interesting challenges

00:32:17.730 --> 00:32:19.760
about the public domain.

00:32:19.760 --> 00:32:25.330
Because of course,
filmmakers are omnivorous.

00:32:25.330 --> 00:32:30.280
We need not one series
of images,

00:32:30.280 --> 00:32:32.620
we need thousands of images.

00:32:32.620 --> 00:32:36.650
While I was sitting here,
I was actually thinking

00:32:36.650 --> 00:32:40.070
like how many - like what would
be the average number of images

00:32:40.070 --> 00:32:44.490
in the 90 minute film, which
is what A Paralyzing Fear was.

00:32:44.490 --> 00:32:47.620
So I thought well an image
on the screen changes

00:32:47.620 --> 00:32:50.610
about once every
five seconds, right?

00:32:50.610 --> 00:32:54.860
So theoretically you could
have somewhere between 900

00:32:54.860 --> 00:33:00.560
and 1,000 images that need
to be somehow collected

00:33:00.560 --> 00:33:06.800
and in any given film, and you
need to either own the right

00:33:06.800 --> 00:33:10.290
to that material, or it has
to be in the public domain,

00:33:10.290 --> 00:33:14.690
which means it's not - it's
free and you can use it at will.

00:33:14.690 --> 00:33:17.940
Well the problem for
documentary filmmakers is

00:33:17.940 --> 00:33:20.560
that we are not just
an omnivorous group,

00:33:20.560 --> 00:33:23.090
but we're an impoverished group.

00:33:23.090 --> 00:33:26.290
And so this issue
of what do we use

00:33:26.290 --> 00:33:30.740
and how do we use it becomes
kind of an interesting,

00:33:30.740 --> 00:33:32.520
I wouldn't say it's
a game that we play,

00:33:32.520 --> 00:33:34.520
but it is a little bit of one.

00:33:34.520 --> 00:33:39.730
And there has become, because of
the kind of voracious appetite

00:33:39.730 --> 00:33:44.010
that documentary filmmakers
have we have become a bit

00:33:44.010 --> 00:33:49.080
of an industry for the both
materials that are in copyright

00:33:49.080 --> 00:33:52.250
and that which is entered
into the public domain.

00:33:52.250 --> 00:33:54.450
Now, the good news for
documentary filmmakers is

00:33:54.450 --> 00:33:58.300
that we don't have to wait
very long because for you know,

00:33:58.300 --> 00:34:00.490
unlike Shakespeare where
we had to wait for many,

00:34:00.490 --> 00:34:03.080
many years for that to
enter the public domain,

00:34:03.080 --> 00:34:07.020
in documentary much
of what has come

00:34:07.020 --> 00:34:09.700
into the public domain
were works created

00:34:09.700 --> 00:34:12.960
by the Federal Government
themselves, which is interesting

00:34:12.960 --> 00:34:18.020
because the Federal Government
is indeed a very large producer

00:34:18.020 --> 00:34:19.580
of filmed work.

00:34:19.580 --> 00:34:22.520
So there is an unending
repository

00:34:22.520 --> 00:34:26.270
that I send my students out
into College Park Maryland

00:34:26.270 --> 00:34:28.890
and they have to go look,
like on a treasure hunt

00:34:28.890 --> 00:34:31.230
for some of these images.

00:34:31.230 --> 00:34:35.650
Because they are fertile
territory for great stories

00:34:35.650 --> 00:34:39.240
and the kinds of material
that we love to use in films,

00:34:39.240 --> 00:34:41.060
because A, there's a lot of it.

00:34:41.060 --> 00:34:42.520
And B, it's free.

00:34:42.520 --> 00:34:47.340
So, hence my assignment to
you, which is to take a look

00:34:47.340 --> 00:34:51.200
at this clip and I'm going
to talk to you a little bit

00:34:51.200 --> 00:34:55.920
about the problems and the
opportunities of public domain

00:34:55.920 --> 00:34:57.760
as related to this
particular film.

00:34:57.760 --> 00:34:59.060
It's a little five minute clip.

00:34:59.060 --> 00:35:03.580
I kind of pulled a little bit
of a fast one on our AV people,

00:35:03.580 --> 00:35:06.630
so the people who are
livestreaming this may not be

00:35:06.630 --> 00:35:08.480
able to get it because I'm going

00:35:08.480 --> 00:35:10.330
to show another film a
little bit later along

00:35:10.330 --> 00:35:12.440
that is definitely not
in the public domain.

00:35:12.440 --> 00:35:16.090
But this one is the trailer
for A Paralyzing Fear,

00:35:16.090 --> 00:35:19.160
the Story of Polio in America,
which is also on YouTube.

00:35:19.160 --> 00:35:22.150
So, follow me along and
take a look at this clip

00:35:22.150 --> 00:35:25.340
and then we're going to
