00:40:49.470 --> 00:40:55.490
So here was the problem.

00:40:55.490 --> 00:40:59.560
When I decided to make this
film, the - I went to the March

00:40:59.560 --> 00:41:02.400
of Dimes and I said, "I want
to make a film about Polio."

00:41:02.400 --> 00:41:04.660
And they said, "Well you an
everybody else who has ever come

00:41:04.660 --> 00:41:07.180
to us, and the answer is no."

00:41:07.180 --> 00:41:14.450
Because they owned all of the
rights to all of the material.

00:41:14.450 --> 00:41:19.270
So not being one to ever take
no for an answer, I begged

00:41:19.270 --> 00:41:24.840
and I pleaded and I collected
all of the best historians

00:41:24.840 --> 00:41:28.990
of science and medicine and many
famous people who had had Polio

00:41:28.990 --> 00:41:30.320
and they lobbied on my behalf.

00:41:30.320 --> 00:41:35.250
And finally the March of
Dimes said, "Okay we're going

00:41:35.250 --> 00:41:38.420
to let you be the
first filmmaker

00:41:38.420 --> 00:41:43.440
that we have ever
given our archive to.

00:41:43.440 --> 00:41:46.630
There is a warehouse
in Fort Lee, New Jersey

00:41:46.630 --> 00:41:48.700
and we don't know how
many films are there,

00:41:48.700 --> 00:41:50.000
and how many photographs.

00:41:50.000 --> 00:41:51.520
But we're going to
give you the key."

00:41:51.520 --> 00:41:55.210
So I got my trusted
crew together

00:41:55.210 --> 00:41:57.710
and got an 18 wheeler
truck and we went

00:41:57.710 --> 00:41:59.010
up to Fort Lee, New Jersey.

00:41:59.010 --> 00:42:02.700
And sure enough we
pulled out 3,000 films

00:42:02.700 --> 00:42:04.160
and 5,000 photographs.

00:42:04.160 --> 00:42:08.080
It's an interesting
amount of material.

00:42:08.080 --> 00:42:10.890
So, I started looking at
this stuff and I thought

00:42:10.890 --> 00:42:13.080
to myself, well wait a minute.

00:42:13.080 --> 00:42:17.090
The Federal Government
was involved in the fight

00:42:17.090 --> 00:42:23.350
against Polio, so a lot
of this is their footage.

00:42:23.350 --> 00:42:25.480
And as we find out in this piece

00:42:25.480 --> 00:42:28.110
and as you probably
know already,

00:42:28.110 --> 00:42:30.010
the person who really
led the fight

00:42:30.010 --> 00:42:34.240
against Polio was
FDR, as President.

00:42:34.240 --> 00:42:38.510
And so a lot of that material
was also taken during the time

00:42:38.510 --> 00:42:41.360
that he was President
of the United States.

00:42:41.360 --> 00:42:45.070
And was in the FDR
Library at Warm Springs.

00:42:45.070 --> 00:42:49.160
And so honestly I started to
question a little bit the March

00:42:49.160 --> 00:42:51.580
of Dimes claim on this material.

00:42:51.580 --> 00:42:55.680
Now, we came to what we
call a blanket license.

00:42:55.680 --> 00:42:59.140
I paid them a heap of money,
they give me a heap of film

00:42:59.140 --> 00:43:02.310
and photographs,
everybody goes home happy.

00:43:02.310 --> 00:43:06.580
But, in the question of what
was in the public domain,

00:43:06.580 --> 00:43:10.480
it really became kind of a bit
of a head scratcher for me.

00:43:10.480 --> 00:43:13.350
Because I thought wait a minute,
they are claiming copyright

00:43:13.350 --> 00:43:17.170
to something that I know
for a fact they don't own.

00:43:17.170 --> 00:43:20.230
But I decided we're going
to leave that to the side

00:43:20.230 --> 00:43:23.440
for the moment because
some of the material,

00:43:23.440 --> 00:43:27.360
I mean they were a private
foundation with monies raised

00:43:27.360 --> 00:43:29.200
through private funds.

00:43:29.200 --> 00:43:31.070
And so a lot of it was theirs.

00:43:31.070 --> 00:43:34.440
But it was all mixed together.

00:43:34.440 --> 00:43:37.890
And hence, the problem
for the documentarian.

00:43:37.890 --> 00:43:43.560
Is that there is - we live
in the era of motion picture

00:43:43.560 --> 00:43:47.160
and have since the
beginning of the 20th century.

00:43:47.160 --> 00:43:51.320
And where this material
comes from

00:43:51.320 --> 00:43:57.280
and how do you trace it back
becomes a bit of a puzzle.

00:43:57.280 --> 00:44:03.330
Well that puzzle becomes I
think ever more interesting

00:44:03.330 --> 00:44:07.190
because somewhere,
somewhere along the line,

00:44:07.190 --> 00:44:12.020
especially after the cable
industry entered sort

00:44:12.020 --> 00:44:14.960
of the documentary filmmaking
world with the History Channel

00:44:14.960 --> 00:44:17.530
and Discovery Channel and
National Geographic Channel,

00:44:17.530 --> 00:44:19.110
and all of these other channels.

00:44:19.110 --> 00:44:22.310
And the need for documentary
films just exploded,

00:44:22.310 --> 00:44:25.920
so did the need for material

00:44:25.920 --> 00:44:29.360
around which these
films would be made.

00:44:29.360 --> 00:44:34.080
So, many enterprising
young entrepreneurs came

00:44:34.080 --> 00:44:38.610
to Washington, to the Library
of Congress where we are today

00:44:38.610 --> 00:44:41.700
and to the National Archives
where we are down the street,

00:44:41.700 --> 00:44:46.950
and they copied everything,
which is interesting, right?

00:44:46.950 --> 00:44:50.320
Because what they did is
they took everything that was

00:44:50.320 --> 00:44:52.920
in the public domain, and you
have all of these filmmakers

00:44:52.920 --> 00:44:55.630
from all around the
world who was omnivorous

00:44:55.630 --> 00:45:01.350
and finance starved as I am
and they sell the material

00:45:01.350 --> 00:45:03.040
that is in the public domain.

00:45:03.040 --> 00:45:06.130
They don't call it
a right's fee,

00:45:06.130 --> 00:45:08.930
they call it you know
an acquisition fee

00:45:08.930 --> 00:45:11.260
or an administrative fee.

00:45:11.260 --> 00:45:15.620
But in fact, what you're doing
is you're paying for the rights

00:45:15.620 --> 00:45:18.880
to public domain material
because you're sitting

00:45:18.880 --> 00:45:20.960
out in Omaha, Nebraska

00:45:20.960 --> 00:45:23.600
and Nebraska Public
Television wants you

00:45:23.600 --> 00:45:25.880
to make a nice documentary
about you know,

00:45:25.880 --> 00:45:27.790
an issue for which
there is plenty

00:45:27.790 --> 00:45:29.090
of public domain material.

00:45:29.090 --> 00:45:31.220
It's going to cost a
lot of money to send you

00:45:31.220 --> 00:45:34.140
to the National Archive, plus
you probably don't have the time

00:45:34.140 --> 00:45:35.440
that it takes, which
his six weeks

00:45:35.440 --> 00:45:37.150
to get the material we produced.

00:45:37.150 --> 00:45:40.570
So, there is an industry
that has actually developed

00:45:40.570 --> 00:45:43.750
around public domain
material because we are

00:45:43.750 --> 00:45:48.750
as I said a voracious
consumer of material.

00:45:48.750 --> 00:45:53.000
So - but there is still
a lot of question.

00:45:53.000 --> 00:45:56.550
Just in that little clip
alone there are I don't know,

00:45:56.550 --> 00:45:58.650
over 100 images, right?

00:45:58.650 --> 00:46:04.390
From the past and I can promise
you that the March of Dimes,

00:46:04.390 --> 00:46:08.640
nor any other rights holder
knows who owns what to whom.

00:46:08.640 --> 00:46:10.590
We do know that probably the -

00:46:10.590 --> 00:46:12.290
you know the Walt
Disney Material,

00:46:12.290 --> 00:46:14.560
we know who owns that, right?

00:46:14.560 --> 00:46:17.870
But aside from that I can
promise you nobody else is quite

00:46:17.870 --> 00:46:20.830
clear on the - on that subject.

00:46:20.830 --> 00:46:26.230
So, it's an interesting
problem of how do you tether out

00:46:26.230 --> 00:46:28.500
and documentary filmmakers,
I'm not going to bore you

00:46:28.500 --> 00:46:30.300
with the legalities of this.

00:46:30.300 --> 00:46:34.700
I mean lawyers kind of
owing - owning our lives.

00:46:34.700 --> 00:46:37.100
We all documentary
filmmakers carry errors

00:46:37.100 --> 00:46:38.830
and admissions insurance.

00:46:38.830 --> 00:46:40.820
And that guarantees
to a broadcaster

00:46:40.820 --> 00:46:44.660
that when we bring something
to them, that they're not going

00:46:44.660 --> 00:46:47.550
to libel for violation
of copyright,

00:46:47.550 --> 00:46:49.840
but rather we take
the responsibility.

00:46:49.840 --> 00:46:53.860
We take the liability for any
error that we may have incurred

00:46:53.860 --> 00:46:55.990
so that nobody is
held responsible

00:46:55.990 --> 00:46:58.600
at the network level, but the
documentary filmmaker is going

00:46:58.600 --> 00:47:01.450
to take all the responsibility
on him or herself,

00:47:01.450 --> 00:47:03.370
which is quite a burden.

00:47:03.370 --> 00:47:06.720
But the fact is is
that trying to parse

00:47:06.720 --> 00:47:11.730
out where does this stuff come
from, who owns it and when it is

00:47:11.730 --> 00:47:15.520
in the public domain why
am I really paying for it?

00:47:15.520 --> 00:47:20.120
Because it has become a very
large profitable industry

00:47:20.120 --> 00:47:23.660
for many companies, and I
salute them for their you know,

00:47:23.660 --> 00:47:27.090
their enterprise that
have managed to take kind

00:47:27.090 --> 00:47:29.850
of the cabilzation of
American life and turned it

00:47:29.850 --> 00:47:35.430
into quite a profitable
business for them.

00:47:35.430 --> 00:47:40.100
The last little bit I'm going
to talk about is the confusion

00:47:40.100 --> 00:47:42.870
between - amongst documentary
filmmakers and the public

00:47:42.870 --> 00:47:48.760
at large about what is in public
domain and what is fair use.

00:47:48.760 --> 00:47:51.370
Fair use, and my students
do this all the time.

00:47:51.370 --> 00:47:52.670
"Oh I can use that,
its fair use.

00:47:52.670 --> 00:47:54.530
It's on YouTube."

00:47:54.530 --> 00:47:56.830
Uh oh -

00:48:01.040 --> 00:48:03.130
There is a common belief
that if it's out there,

00:48:03.130 --> 00:48:05.890
and I can get it, it's mine.

00:48:05.890 --> 00:48:08.100
And fair use and
I'm not going to go

00:48:08.100 --> 00:48:10.470
into you know the
complications of it,

00:48:10.470 --> 00:48:14.320
is actually a fairly
limited classification

00:48:14.320 --> 00:48:16.100
under which a documentary
filmmaker

00:48:16.100 --> 00:48:18.820
or someone else can
take a piece of material

00:48:18.820 --> 00:48:23.030
that is indeed copyrighted and
used for their own purposes.

00:48:23.030 --> 00:48:26.840
One of those - the central
premise of fair use is

00:48:26.840 --> 00:48:30.640
that the rights holder, if
you're creating a polemic

00:48:30.640 --> 00:48:34.620
of something and they would have
every reason not to grant you -

00:48:34.620 --> 00:48:39.100
not to grant you copyright
in this issue of the polemic

00:48:39.100 --> 00:48:42.540
and it's kind of part of -
in the public discourse then

00:48:42.540 --> 00:48:45.020
that is a pretty
legitimate fair use claim.

00:48:45.020 --> 00:48:49.430
I'm going to show you a clip
from my most recent work

00:48:49.430 --> 00:48:51.900
and this cannot be streamed
because the question

00:48:51.900 --> 00:48:56.790
of fair use has yet to
be fought on this one.

00:48:56.790 --> 00:49:00.910
But it does pose sort of
an interesting challenge

00:49:00.910 --> 00:49:05.970
to who owns what and how much
documentary filmmakers sort

00:49:05.970 --> 00:49:07.730
of claim for themselves.

00:49:07.730 --> 00:49:11.930
Anyway, this is a clip from my
new project called My Fugitive.

00:49:11.930 --> 00:49:13.940
And will not be streamed.

00:49:13.940 --> 00:49:16.910
What I found, and I'm not
going to tell you everything.

00:49:16.910 --> 00:49:19.760
The project will
drop on May 4, 2020,

00:49:19.760 --> 00:49:23.770
which is the 50th anniversary
of the Kent State Murders,

00:49:23.770 --> 00:49:26.700
was the connection between what
happened to Howard Becanick

00:49:26.700 --> 00:49:28.600
and his other co-defendants.

00:49:28.600 --> 00:49:31.670
And the investigation
into the conspiracy

00:49:31.670 --> 00:49:34.780
to assassinate Dr.
Martin Luther King.

00:49:34.780 --> 00:49:39.210
So, the question as to what is
going to enter into fair use

00:49:39.210 --> 00:49:42.470
on this particular
project is going to be kind

00:49:42.470 --> 00:49:43.770
of a long and protractive one.

00:49:43.770 --> 00:49:45.930
I have great legal
representation.

00:49:45.930 --> 00:49:50.840
So - but it is an
interesting kind of conundrum -

00:49:50.840 --> 00:49:53.540
for documentary filmmakers
between what is

00:49:53.540 --> 00:49:57.430
in the public domain and what
is available to us for fair use,

00:49:57.430 --> 00:50:01.160
which is an altogether other
and interesting dialog.

00:50:01.160 --> 00:50:03.600
On that note, I'd like to
conclude, and I thank you

00:50:03.600 --> 00:50:05.510
for your time and
appreciate your attention.

