00:51:16.050 --> 00:51:18.170
in Culpepper, Virginia.

00:51:18.170 --> 00:51:20.070
In addition, there
are many private

00:51:20.070 --> 00:51:23.590
and non-profit online resources
for public domain works,

00:51:23.590 --> 00:51:25.910
including Project
Gutenberg, HathiTrust,

00:51:25.910 --> 00:51:29.020
Amazon, Kindle and Google.

00:51:29.020 --> 00:51:31.280
So, onto musicals.

00:51:31.280 --> 00:51:33.980
A quintessentially
American art form.

00:51:33.980 --> 00:51:37.640
From the late 19th century to
today musicals have evolved

00:51:37.640 --> 00:51:41.170
in form, narrative
and production.

00:51:41.170 --> 00:51:42.860
This year, musical works

00:51:42.860 --> 00:51:45.680
from multiple productions
enter the public domain,

00:51:45.680 --> 00:51:49.760
including the Rise of Rose
O'Reilly by George M. Cohan,

00:51:49.760 --> 00:51:53.380
A Perfect Lady by George
Gershwin, Music Box Revue

00:51:53.380 --> 00:51:58.170
by Irving Berlin and the
Wallflower by Oscar Hammerstein.

00:51:58.170 --> 00:52:00.800
Our next presenter
is Benjamin West.

00:52:00.800 --> 00:52:03.670
A director, producer, performer,

00:52:03.670 --> 00:52:06.310
writer and musical
theater historian.

00:52:06.310 --> 00:52:09.560
His current projects
include the Showtime Trilogy,

00:52:09.560 --> 00:52:11.650
Direct from Proctors
23rd Street Theater

00:52:11.650 --> 00:52:14.730
for one night only,
January 16, 1920.

00:52:14.730 --> 00:52:16.880
And 514 Broadway.

00:52:16.880 --> 00:52:20.390
West's directing credits
include Unsung Caroline Lee

00:52:20.390 --> 00:52:23.850
for Lincoln Center's American
Songbook, Gatsby the Songs

00:52:23.850 --> 00:52:28.170
and Concert, Make Mine Manhattan
and the Fig Leaves are Falling.

00:52:28.170 --> 00:52:31.660
His Broadway credits include
assistant director and drama

00:52:31.660 --> 00:52:36.400
for Old Acquaintance, assistant
producer for August Osage County

00:52:36.400 --> 00:52:40.510
and the Homecoming, and product
assistant for Talk Radio.

00:52:40.510 --> 00:52:43.320
He is the founder of
Unsung Musical Company,

00:52:43.320 --> 00:52:48.780
a 2017 recipient of Lincoln
Center's Martin E. Segal Award.

00:52:48.780 --> 00:52:51.940
He will share with us
a case study in the use

00:52:51.940 --> 00:52:55.130
of public domain works from his
documentary musical series The

00:52:55.130 --> 00:52:56.450
Showtime Trilogy.

00:52:56.450 --> 00:53:00.400
The second installment of this
trilogy entitled 45 Minutes

00:53:00.400 --> 00:53:03.810
from Coon Town, a Celebration
of Black Musical Theater,

00:53:03.810 --> 00:53:06.010
tracing its history
from the late 1800's

00:53:06.010 --> 00:53:09.430
through 1999 will
open on September 12,

00:53:09.430 --> 00:53:14.750
2019 at the York Theater
Company in New York City.

00:53:14.750 --> 00:53:17.510
So, without further
ado Benjamin West.

00:53:17.510 --> 00:53:28.100
[ Applause ]

00:53:28.100 --> 00:53:30.400
&gt;&gt; Benjamin West: Good morning.

00:53:35.640 --> 00:53:37.080
Thank you Whitney.

00:53:37.080 --> 00:53:40.980
I am Ben West, and I am
a musical theater artist

00:53:40.980 --> 00:53:42.670
and historian.

00:53:42.670 --> 00:53:46.670
My focus and my passion
is really two fold.

00:53:46.670 --> 00:53:50.160
One illuminating the
intersection of past, present

00:53:50.160 --> 00:53:53.800
and future, effectively
how successive generations

00:53:53.800 --> 00:53:57.210
of artists and audiences
continue to influence

00:53:57.210 --> 00:54:01.790
and inform one another, and
two exploring how the American

00:54:01.790 --> 00:54:05.440
musical is a reflection
of American consciousness.

00:54:05.440 --> 00:54:09.000
So effectively it's
capturing our social, cultural

00:54:09.000 --> 00:54:12.160
and political sensibilities
at any moment

00:54:12.160 --> 00:54:14.580
in time throughout its history.

00:54:14.580 --> 00:54:18.330
There are two quotes that
speak to both of these themes

00:54:18.330 --> 00:54:22.090
and I happen to love,
one is by a lyricist

00:54:22.090 --> 00:54:24.260
and composer Harold Rome,

00:54:24.260 --> 00:54:27.310
who was a tremendous
Broadway review writer,

00:54:27.310 --> 00:54:31.250
and also wrote a number of book
musicals, Destry Rides Again

00:54:31.250 --> 00:54:33.450
and Fanny are two of his shows.

00:54:33.450 --> 00:54:37.570
And he says whether you want to
be original, or whether you want

00:54:37.570 --> 00:54:41.710
to be conventional you still
have to know what has been done

00:54:41.710 --> 00:54:44.090
in order to be either.

00:54:44.090 --> 00:54:46.150
This is a quote that
I particularly love.

00:54:46.150 --> 00:54:48.980
And the other one is from
YipHarburg who you'll know

00:54:48.980 --> 00:54:51.900
as the lyricist of
the Wizard of Oz,

00:54:51.900 --> 00:54:53.710
of Brother Can you Spare a Dime

00:54:53.710 --> 00:54:55.750
and a number of Broadway
musicals.

00:54:55.750 --> 00:55:00.600
And he says, "A songwriter
is really a journalist

00:55:00.600 --> 00:55:02.810
of time with music."

00:55:02.810 --> 00:55:06.040
So both of these
quotes certainly feed me

00:55:06.040 --> 00:55:08.500
and I think feed my focus.

00:55:08.500 --> 00:55:12.770
And with these two focuses
I'm looking a lot at writers,

00:55:12.770 --> 00:55:17.100
creators, craftsman of the form
and my projects tend to deal

00:55:17.100 --> 00:55:19.600
with the history of
the American musical

00:55:19.600 --> 00:55:21.740
in some way, shape or form.

00:55:21.740 --> 00:55:23.460
And in dealing with the history

00:55:23.460 --> 00:55:26.680
of the American musical
I am working a lot

00:55:26.680 --> 00:55:29.650
with public domain materials.

00:55:29.650 --> 00:55:32.840
And in fact all five of
these songs that you see

00:55:32.840 --> 00:55:36.980
up here are currently in
public domain, and all five

00:55:36.980 --> 00:55:39.630
of these songs are
also incorporated

00:55:39.630 --> 00:55:44.470
into my current project,
which is the Showtime Trilogy.

00:55:44.470 --> 00:55:48.290
And with that, I'll give you a
brief background on the trilogy

00:55:48.290 --> 00:55:51.440
and then we're going to look
at two specific sequences

00:55:51.440 --> 00:55:55.290
so we can have a sense of how
public domain works are used

00:55:55.290 --> 00:55:58.040
in the creation of
this new work.

00:55:58.040 --> 00:56:02.550
The Showtime Trilogy is a
project I began developing

00:56:02.550 --> 00:56:06.770
about five years ago now, almost
five years ago and research

00:56:06.770 --> 00:56:10.080
for the piece has taken me to
more than 20 different archives

00:56:10.080 --> 00:56:12.980
across the country,
including here in DC,

00:56:12.980 --> 00:56:15.800
the Library of Congress of
course, the copyright office

00:56:15.800 --> 00:56:19.180
and actually also Howard
University, I should mention.

00:56:19.180 --> 00:56:25.080
The trilogy is three documentary
musicals which celebrate

00:56:25.080 --> 00:56:29.130
and chart the history
of the American musical.

00:56:29.130 --> 00:56:33.350
Now the project aims to be
comprehensive in its coverage,

00:56:33.350 --> 00:56:38.410
so we go back to minstrelsy
and vaudeville in the 1800's.

00:56:38.410 --> 00:56:41.940
We move through the turn of
the century musical burlesque

00:56:41.940 --> 00:56:45.660
and American operetta,
George M. Cohan and so forth,

00:56:45.660 --> 00:56:48.950
all the way to the
works of George C. Wolfe

00:56:48.950 --> 00:56:53.450
and Jason Robert Brown in the
1990's and the cut off point

00:56:53.450 --> 00:56:56.470
for the project is 1999.

00:56:56.470 --> 00:57:00.250
In terms of the documentary
musical construct.

00:57:00.250 --> 00:57:02.980
It is a form that
I've been developing

00:57:02.980 --> 00:57:04.280
over the past several years,

00:57:04.280 --> 00:57:06.580
and I do believe it's
unique in its form.

00:57:06.580 --> 00:57:11.620
We are essentially weaving
live music and live performance

00:57:11.620 --> 00:57:14.580
through this non-fiction
historical narrative

00:57:14.580 --> 00:57:17.810
to tell the story of
the American musical.

00:57:17.810 --> 00:57:21.070
Now each piece is
designed as a solo show.

00:57:21.070 --> 00:57:24.350
And the narrator is very
much an omniscient vessel,

00:57:24.350 --> 00:57:26.560
through whom the
history flows forth,

00:57:26.560 --> 00:57:29.440
and in whom the various
styles of music

00:57:29.440 --> 00:57:32.310
and performance are embodied.

00:57:32.310 --> 00:57:35.410
Each piece, I should also
mention is fully scripted

00:57:35.410 --> 00:57:37.470
and so it is a fully
scripted musical.

00:57:37.470 --> 00:57:40.450
Again, it's non-fiction,
so we're not talking

00:57:40.450 --> 00:57:43.790
about a historical or
biographic dramatization,

00:57:43.790 --> 00:57:46.390
but it's actually
documentary in nature.

00:57:46.390 --> 00:57:50.800
And as such, we're
utilizing narration, quotes,

00:57:50.800 --> 00:57:55.230
newspaper articles and existing
songs to tell this story

00:57:55.230 --> 00:57:58.090
of a uniquely American art form.

00:57:58.090 --> 00:58:01.530
And it's very much; I should
point out an active story.

00:58:01.530 --> 00:58:04.160
It's a very active,
theatrical story.

00:58:04.160 --> 00:58:08.490
And in terms of the songs the
trilogy all told uses more

00:58:08.490 --> 00:58:13.840
than 100 songs in the telling of
this story, 100 existing songs.

00:58:13.840 --> 00:58:16.220
And that's 100 -
more than 100 songs

00:58:16.220 --> 00:58:18.280
over all three installments.

00:58:18.280 --> 00:58:21.690
So, I'll break down quickly
the installments for you.

00:58:21.690 --> 00:58:25.660
The first installment and
primary entry is Showtime,

00:58:25.660 --> 00:58:29.050
the First 100 years of
the American Musical.

00:58:29.050 --> 00:58:32.700
And this really looks at the
evolution of the form itself

00:58:32.700 --> 00:58:34.330
and its cultural impact.

00:58:34.330 --> 00:58:36.320
And just a quick
example of what I mean

00:58:36.320 --> 00:58:37.810
by the evolution of the form.

00:58:37.810 --> 00:58:43.030
New York Time article 1907 this
is - it reads in part talking

00:58:43.030 --> 00:58:45.870
about the form about the
musical, this American musical.

00:58:45.870 --> 00:58:51.650
New York Times 1907,
"Fashions in plays may change,

00:58:51.650 --> 00:58:56.220
but musical comedy remains about
the same from beginning to end.

00:58:56.220 --> 00:58:58.370
It is taken as a
matter of course

00:58:58.370 --> 00:59:00.560
that the tunes will
be reminiscent.

00:59:00.560 --> 00:59:04.660
The characters are nearly always
the same and the comedy in many

00:59:04.660 --> 00:59:09.020
of these shows is
the saddest feature.

00:59:09.020 --> 00:59:13.720
There are, as a rule, only
two classes of musical comedy.

00:59:13.720 --> 00:59:16.750
The good and the bad."

00:59:16.750 --> 00:59:20.620
And then we jump forward 40
years and Alan J. Lerner,

00:59:20.620 --> 00:59:23.050
who you'll know as the
author of My Fair Lady

00:59:23.050 --> 00:59:28.070
and Brigadoon speaking about the
American musical, again 1947.

00:59:28.070 --> 00:59:31.370
And he says, "The
musical theater

00:59:31.370 --> 00:59:36.440
in America is becoming a vital
medium of dramatic expression.

00:59:36.440 --> 00:59:40.050
With words, music and
movement, blended together

00:59:40.050 --> 00:59:45.790
in complete synchronization
a real art form is revealed."

00:59:45.790 --> 00:59:49.220
So Showtime is essentially
looking at this evolution

00:59:49.220 --> 00:59:52.860
from minstrelsy, vaudeville,
early musical comedy

00:59:52.860 --> 00:59:56.990
into the real art form being
revealed and through to the 90s.

00:59:56.990 --> 01:00:01.340
I'll also point out this first
installment premiered this past

01:00:01.340 --> 01:00:03.740
September at the
Theater at St. Peter's.

01:00:03.740 --> 01:00:07.020
And the second installment
45 Minutes

01:00:07.020 --> 01:00:09.990
from Coon Town will premier
this coming September

01:00:09.990 --> 01:00:11.440
at the same venue.

01:00:11.440 --> 01:00:15.060
45 Minutes from Coon
Town is specifically

01:00:15.060 --> 01:00:20.060
about Black musicals and
Black writers in particular.

01:00:20.060 --> 01:00:24.500
And the third and final
installment is 68 Ways to Go,

01:00:24.500 --> 01:00:27.480
which is about female
musical theater, writers

01:00:27.480 --> 01:00:30.090
and that will premier in 2020.

01:00:30.090 --> 01:00:33.670
And then the plan is to premier
the trilogy in its entirety

01:00:33.670 --> 01:00:38.980
in 2021 where we will have
each show in succession.

01:00:38.980 --> 01:00:43.760
Now that's the trilogy and we'll
take a look at two sequences

01:00:43.760 --> 01:00:47.120
from the primary entry Show
time the First 100 years

01:00:47.120 --> 01:00:50.310
to give a sense of how public
domain material has been used

01:00:50.310 --> 01:00:53.250
in creating the narrative
and creating the peace.

01:00:53.250 --> 01:00:55.850
Showtime the First 100 years,

01:00:55.850 --> 01:01:01.690
the primary entry utilizes
59 existing songs in total,

01:01:01.690 --> 01:01:04.540
21 of those are public domain

01:01:04.540 --> 01:01:07.210
and 38 are still
under copyright.

01:01:07.210 --> 01:01:09.960
The show is two acts, including
the intermission it runs

01:01:09.960 --> 01:01:12.550
about 2:20, 2:25.

01:01:12.550 --> 01:01:15.540
We'll look at two
specific songs that are

01:01:15.540 --> 01:01:18.110
in Showtime the first 100 Years.

01:01:18.110 --> 01:01:22.880
They are Jazz Baby
and Prohibition Blues.

01:01:22.880 --> 01:01:26.380
Completely coincidentally
both are from 1919

01:01:26.380 --> 01:01:30.890
and both are co-authored
by a female writer.

01:01:30.890 --> 01:01:34.110
Jazz Baby has lyrics
by Blanche Merrill

01:01:34.110 --> 01:01:39.930
and Prohibition Blues
has music by Nora Bayes.

01:01:39.930 --> 01:01:44.570
Now when we encounter these
songs in Showtime it's

01:01:44.570 --> 01:01:47.820
in a scene that deals with
the early 20th century.

01:01:47.820 --> 01:01:50.720
We begin the scene talking
about the various musical styles

01:01:50.720 --> 01:01:53.360
that are spreading across
the stage at that time.

01:01:53.360 --> 01:01:58.460
And then we get to rag time
and its evolution into jazz.

01:01:58.460 --> 01:02:00.850
And you'll see we come
to Jazz Baby here.

01:02:00.850 --> 01:02:02.930
So, just a brief
point about part

01:02:02.930 --> 01:02:04.440
of the language of the show.

01:02:04.440 --> 01:02:08.800
The lyric in almost all of the
songs was specifically chosen

01:02:08.800 --> 01:02:13.060
to filter into the narrative,
to become part of the narrative.

01:02:13.060 --> 01:02:15.420
So we mention rag time evolving,

01:02:15.420 --> 01:02:17.430
but we don't actually
mention jazz.

01:02:17.430 --> 01:02:20.950
And so the question of into
what does it evolve is answered

01:02:20.950 --> 01:02:22.250
through the song.

01:02:22.250 --> 01:02:26.700
So music comes in and we have
the first chorus of jazz baby

01:02:26.700 --> 01:02:30.040
and then you'll see music
under at the bottom of that.

01:02:30.040 --> 01:02:32.680
Again another part of the
language in storytelling

01:02:32.680 --> 01:02:36.840
in this particular show, music
is woven through the narrative

01:02:36.840 --> 01:02:38.700
through much of the show.

01:02:38.700 --> 01:02:40.180
So you'll see music
will continue

01:02:40.180 --> 01:02:43.230
under for an Irving
Berlin quote.

01:02:43.230 --> 01:02:45.330
And again speaking
further to the language

01:02:45.330 --> 01:02:47.370
of the show you'll
see a parenthetical

01:02:47.370 --> 01:02:48.670
that says down beats only.

01:02:48.670 --> 01:02:50.580
Then we have one line of dialog

01:02:50.580 --> 01:02:53.900
and then we have music
full for the quote.

01:02:53.900 --> 01:02:57.050
Music and also acoustic
sounds effects that are made

01:02:57.050 --> 01:03:01.300
by the drummer and his various
toys are used throughout the

01:03:01.300 --> 01:03:03.180
show, throughout
the entire piece

01:03:03.180 --> 01:03:08.590
as really connective tissue, and
also as oral quotation marks.

01:03:08.590 --> 01:03:11.540
So, when you see - we're going
to show a video clip of this,

01:03:11.540 --> 01:03:14.030
you'll see that there's going
to be just downbeats only

01:03:14.030 --> 01:03:17.460
for two bars where we set up the
quote, and then music will come

01:03:17.460 --> 01:03:19.800
in fully under the quote itself.

01:03:19.800 --> 01:03:22.320
So, it's to help
differentiate and delineate

01:03:22.320 --> 01:03:26.080
between what is narration
and what is the actual quote.

01:03:26.080 --> 01:03:29.730
Following the Irving Berlin
quote we go into another bit

01:03:29.730 --> 01:03:32.530
of Jazz Baby and then you'll
see music under - at the bottom

01:03:32.530 --> 01:03:34.620
of the screen here, stop time.

01:03:34.620 --> 01:03:36.480
So we're going to go
music under again,

01:03:36.480 --> 01:03:39.390
this time for a Rosamond
Johnson quote.

01:03:39.390 --> 01:03:41.560
He was an early Black composer.

01:03:41.560 --> 01:03:44.490
And this is going to be
speaking about Negro spirituals

01:03:44.490 --> 01:03:48.200
and the routes of this form
and essentially harking back

01:03:48.200 --> 01:03:50.930
to slavery - harkening
back to slavery.

01:03:50.930 --> 01:03:55.680
And in so doing the feel of the
underscore is entirely different

01:03:55.680 --> 01:03:58.790
than the feel of the more
celebratory Irving Berlin quote.

01:03:58.790 --> 01:04:02.250
We're going to be in stop time,
which you'll see in a moment.

01:04:02.250 --> 01:04:04.780
And also you'll notice
that it's going to go minor

01:04:04.780 --> 01:04:06.630
in what we're talking about.

01:04:06.630 --> 01:04:11.130
And music will cut out after
that, so I'll stop there,

01:04:11.130 --> 01:04:12.850
and then we're going to take
a look at the video right now.

01:04:12.850 --> 01:04:15.770
I want to mention just
three quick points.

01:04:15.770 --> 01:04:18.660
My music collaborator
for the entire trilogy,

01:04:18.660 --> 01:04:21.310
all three installments
is Fran Menaric

01:04:21.310 --> 01:04:24.480
who has created all new
arrangements for all

01:04:24.480 --> 01:04:26.840
of the songs, and
helped me to weave them

01:04:26.840 --> 01:04:28.940
through the narrative
quite literally.

01:04:28.940 --> 01:04:31.960
Our director and musical stager

01:04:31.960 --> 01:04:36.170
for Showtime the First 100
years is Shannon Lewis.

01:04:36.170 --> 01:04:39.880
And then at the beginning of
the clip there is a drum roll,

01:04:39.880 --> 01:04:41.900
that's not actually
part of the script.

01:04:41.900 --> 01:04:44.330
That is just setting
up the clip;

01:04:44.330 --> 01:04:46.490
so disregard the drum roll.

01:04:46.490 --> 01:04:51.510
All right, so let's take a look
at this Jazz Baby sequence.

01:04:51.510 --> 01:06:46.510
[ Music ]

01:06:46.510 --> 01:06:51.580
[ Applause ]

01:06:51.580 --> 01:06:55.870
So that is a bit of
the Jazz Baby sequence.

01:06:55.870 --> 01:06:59.010
And in fact, it continues
right on.

01:06:59.010 --> 01:07:02.100
There's no break from the
Rosamond Johnson quote,

01:07:02.100 --> 01:07:04.570
we go into a socio
political section,

01:07:04.570 --> 01:07:06.830
small sociopolitical section.

01:07:06.830 --> 01:07:10.780
Because again, one of the themes
being the American musical

01:07:10.780 --> 01:07:13.660
as a reflection of our
social consciousness.

01:07:13.660 --> 01:07:16.550
So again from Rosamond
Johnson we go directly

01:07:16.550 --> 01:07:20.510
into a section about
Black writers.

01:07:20.510 --> 01:07:23.730
And so I actually have a
question for everyone here.

01:07:23.730 --> 01:07:29.770
I wonder if anyone can name any
Black musical theater writers

01:07:29.770 --> 01:07:35.130
working early 20th
century, 1900 to 1930?

01:07:35.130 --> 01:07:36.930
Any guesses?

01:07:36.930 --> 01:07:39.920
[ Inaudible ]

01:07:39.920 --> 01:07:41.220
Yes.

01:07:41.220 --> 01:07:43.060
[ Inaudible ]

01:07:43.060 --> 01:07:44.790
Yes, Colin Johnson for sure.

01:07:44.790 --> 01:07:46.430
Yes, awesome.

01:07:46.430 --> 01:07:52.410
Great. So there were actually
quite a few Black writers

01:07:52.410 --> 01:07:55.250
working on Broadway in
the early 20th century,

01:07:55.250 --> 01:07:56.550
relatively speaking.

01:07:56.550 --> 01:07:59.510
Certainly the form was still
dominated by White men.

01:07:59.510 --> 01:08:02.280
But there were a tremendous
number of Black artists.

01:08:02.280 --> 01:08:05.210
I'll point out Bob
Cole who you mentioned,

01:08:05.210 --> 01:08:08.400
who I consider the father
of Black musical theater.

01:08:08.400 --> 01:08:13.490
He is - he devised what is
considered the first full length

01:08:13.490 --> 01:08:17.690
legitimate Black musical
comedy, A Trip to Coon Town.

01:08:17.690 --> 01:08:22.200
This was in 1897 and that is
the Coon Town that we reference

01:08:22.200 --> 01:08:24.870
in our 45 Minutes
from Coon Town title.

01:08:24.870 --> 01:08:29.130
And I'll also mention at the
top there, James P. Johnson

01:08:29.130 --> 01:08:31.410
and then toward the
middle Cecil Mack

01:08:31.410 --> 01:08:33.340
because they wrote
the Charleston,

01:08:33.340 --> 01:08:34.770
which you heard earlier.

01:08:34.770 --> 01:08:38.130
And that was from
1923, which you pointed

01:08:38.130 --> 01:08:41.920
out from a Black musical
called Running Wild.

01:08:41.920 --> 01:08:45.460
And then from the Black
author section we jump right

01:08:45.460 --> 01:08:48.370
into female writers
and so again I wonder,

01:08:48.370 --> 01:08:53.120
can anyone name any female
musical theater writers working

01:08:53.120 --> 01:08:56.540
early 20th century,
1900's to 1930?

01:08:56.540 --> 01:08:58.840
Any guesses?

01:09:02.040 --> 01:09:03.880
There were also quite a
number of women working.

01:09:03.880 --> 01:09:07.000
Dorothy Fields, I
think you probably -

01:09:07.000 --> 01:09:09.120
if you don't know the name,
you probably know her work.

01:09:09.120 --> 01:09:12.140
I can't give you anything but
Love Baby, on the Sunny Side

01:09:12.140 --> 01:09:15.200
of the Street, a
number of pop standards.

01:09:15.200 --> 01:09:18.590
I want to also call attention
to Alma Sanders who is

01:09:18.590 --> 01:09:23.120
at the bottom right
of the screen.

01:09:23.120 --> 01:09:26.140
Because her, a bit
of her story speaks

01:09:26.140 --> 01:09:30.550
to how essentially the social
dynamics are informing the

01:09:30.550 --> 01:09:31.990
American musical.

01:09:31.990 --> 01:09:35.330
She eventually moved to New
York, but was actually living

01:09:35.330 --> 01:09:38.480
in Detroit when she
began her career.

01:09:38.480 --> 01:09:40.770
She would eventually
marry her lyricist,

01:09:40.770 --> 01:09:42.070
her lyric writing partner.

01:09:42.070 --> 01:09:43.920
He would be her second husband.

01:09:43.920 --> 01:09:46.190
She was married to her first
husband at the time though

01:09:46.190 --> 01:09:50.010
in Detroit, who wanted to
get a divorce from her.

01:09:50.010 --> 01:09:53.230
And she was on the
cusp of breaking

01:09:53.230 --> 01:09:54.770
through in the musical theater.

01:09:54.770 --> 01:09:57.670
She would go on to write a
handful of shows in the 20's

01:09:57.670 --> 01:10:01.090
and in 1921 is when
the divorce happened.

01:10:01.090 --> 01:10:07.440
So I'll read, this is from the
Detroit Free Press March 1921.

01:10:07.440 --> 01:10:11.610
"Ernest E. Benjamin was
granted a divorce from his wife,

01:10:11.610 --> 01:10:14.540
the well-known song
writer Alma Sanders.

01:10:14.540 --> 01:10:17.500
Benjamin testified
that his wife's success

01:10:17.500 --> 01:10:21.120
in writing two song
hits turned her head.

01:10:21.120 --> 01:10:23.510
And she refused to
keep house any longer.

01:10:23.510 --> 01:10:26.810
[ Laughter ]

01:10:26.810 --> 01:10:29.360
Or, to live in Detroit.

01:10:31.880 --> 01:10:35.970
He said she spent much of
her time in New York coming

01:10:35.970 --> 01:10:38.690
and going as she pleased."

01:10:38.690 --> 01:10:42.660
So that's just a fun little bit.

01:10:42.660 --> 01:10:44.740
I'm in the midst of writing
the women's show right now,

01:10:44.740 --> 01:10:46.040
we start readings next week.

01:10:46.040 --> 01:10:48.820
So I enjoy her story.

01:10:48.820 --> 01:10:54.870
And so then, from female
writers we cap this jazz

01:10:54.870 --> 01:10:58.340
and sociopolitical sequence
with prohibition blues

01:10:58.340 --> 01:11:01.190
and we get there - again
we're early 20th century;

01:11:01.190 --> 01:11:05.530
so that's women's right to
vote being ratified in 1920,

01:11:05.530 --> 01:11:08.070
also income tax and prohibition.

01:11:08.070 --> 01:11:10.880
So again, prohibition
blues brings us back

01:11:10.880 --> 01:11:12.540
to the jazz vernacular.

01:11:12.540 --> 01:11:16.300
We'll play the prohibition
blues clip now and then I'll pop

01:11:16.300 --> 01:11:19.080
up the script page for
it immediately after.

01:11:19.080 --> 01:11:23.510
So, this is prohibition blues.

01:11:23.510 --> 01:12:48.510
[ Music ]

01:12:48.510 --> 01:12:51.620
[ Applause ]

01:12:51.620 --> 01:12:54.830
And I just want to
mention again, the music is

01:12:54.830 --> 01:12:56.140
by Nora Bayes who is one

01:12:56.140 --> 01:13:00.020
of the first female
musical theater composers,

01:13:00.020 --> 01:13:01.810
who I happen to love.

01:13:01.810 --> 01:13:05.470
She was a very big
vaudeville and stage star.

01:13:05.470 --> 01:13:07.940
And so here's just a quick
look at the script page

01:13:07.940 --> 01:13:09.520
for prohibition blues.

01:13:09.520 --> 01:13:11.940
Again you'll see we cap the idea

01:13:11.940 --> 01:13:13.950
of social consciousness
at the top.

01:13:13.950 --> 01:13:16.930
We go into prohibition blues,
again part of the language,

01:13:16.930 --> 01:13:20.640
the music will continue under
for a final quote about jazz

01:13:20.640 --> 01:13:23.630
to wrap up and come full
circle with this jazz sequence

01:13:23.630 --> 01:13:25.340
and then we move forward.

01:13:25.340 --> 01:13:29.500
Just in terms of using
the songs in the narrative

01:13:29.500 --> 01:13:32.430
and in telling the story these
two songs were used almost

01:13:32.430 --> 01:13:34.450
in their entirety, but
that's not the case

01:13:34.450 --> 01:13:35.750
with all of the songs.

01:13:35.750 --> 01:13:39.430
In some cases we use
just two or three lines,

01:13:39.430 --> 01:13:42.500
in some cases we just use a
chorus; so it really depends

01:13:42.500 --> 01:13:44.320
on the needs of the
specific moment

01:13:44.320 --> 01:13:47.410
and how the song is utilized
in the story telling.

01:13:47.410 --> 01:13:53.020
And with that I think
I have completed.

01:13:53.020 --> 01:13:58.350
So that is how essentially the
songs are used in the show.

01:13:58.350 --> 01:14:00.510
And thank you for your time.

01:14:00.510 --> 01:14:19.040
[ Applause ]

01:14:19.040 --> 01:14:20.910
&gt;&gt; Whitney Levandusky:
Thank you so much Ben.

01:14:20.910 --> 01:14:24.970
Before we go, there
is a fourth speaker

01:14:24.970 --> 01:14:27.300
that we were hoping
to have here today.

01:14:27.300 --> 01:14:32.550
I want to take a moment to
highlight a powerful example

01:14:32.550 --> 01:14:37.850
of how the use of public
domain works can help us better

01:14:37.850 --> 01:14:43.610
understand ourselves
and our current time.

01:14:43.610 --> 01:14:45.680
Nina's presentation highlighted

01:14:45.680 --> 01:14:49.540
for us the way documentarians
use the public domain

01:14:49.540 --> 01:14:52.480
to bring truth and
understanding to often difficult

01:14:52.480 --> 01:14:54.930
and painful experiences.

01:14:56.800 --> 01:14:59.450
We were hoping to
have Taina Caragol,

01:14:59.450 --> 01:15:02.680
Curator at the Smithsonian
National Portrait Gallery join

01:15:02.680 --> 01:15:05.360
us today to discuss
the works included

01:15:05.360 --> 01:15:10.490
in the recent exhibition,
Unseen our past in a new light,

01:15:10.490 --> 01:15:15.580
to highlight a similar
practice among visual artists.

01:15:15.580 --> 01:15:18.030
Unfortunately because of
the government shutdown,

01:15:18.030 --> 01:15:21.420
she is unable to participate
in the event today.

01:15:21.420 --> 01:15:25.020
Caragol co-curated with
Osman Naim the works

01:15:25.020 --> 01:15:30.120
of Ken Gonzalez Day and Titus
Kafar to product an exhibition

01:15:30.120 --> 01:15:33.820
that considers the intersections
between portraiture,

01:15:33.820 --> 01:15:37.810
nation building and
museum practice.

01:15:37.810 --> 01:15:39.690
A brief warning before we begin,

01:15:39.690 --> 01:15:43.840
the images that follow directly
content with America's history

01:15:43.840 --> 01:15:46.620
of slavery and lynching.

01:15:46.620 --> 01:15:50.030
Gonzalez Day photographs
historical objects,

01:15:50.030 --> 01:15:54.130
be they from archives or museums
and suggests new meanings

01:15:54.130 --> 01:15:56.490
for them by thoughtfully
altering their composition

01:15:56.490 --> 01:15:58.790
or display.

01:16:12.420 --> 01:16:16.640
Here we have two works from
his erased lynching series.

01:16:16.640 --> 01:16:21.180
This series Gonzalez Day tells
us was sparked in response

01:16:21.180 --> 01:16:25.130
to anti-immigration rhetoric
that directly led to an increase

01:16:25.130 --> 01:16:28.900
in vigilante activity
along the US/Mexican border

01:16:28.900 --> 01:16:31.370
in the early 2000's.

01:16:31.370 --> 01:16:35.840
Each image is a recasting
of lynching photograph

01:16:35.840 --> 01:16:40.960
that took place in the United
States between 1850 and 1942.

01:16:40.960 --> 01:16:46.800
Where Gonzalez Day rephotographs
the image and removes the victim

01:16:46.800 --> 01:16:50.190
and the hanging materials
from the composition.

01:16:50.190 --> 01:16:54.920
Gonzalez Day has researched and
uncovered 350 cases of lynching

01:16:54.920 --> 01:16:58.690
in the state of California
alone as detailed in his book,

01:16:58.690 --> 01:17:03.310
Lynching in the West,
1850 to 1935.

01:17:03.310 --> 01:17:07.420
As Caragol states, in
unseen's catalog rather

01:17:07.420 --> 01:17:10.660
than inflicting more
violence upon the victims,

01:17:10.660 --> 01:17:14.020
Gonzalez Day directs our
attention to perpetrators

01:17:14.020 --> 01:17:18.700
and bystanders to consider
mob violence nationwide,

01:17:18.700 --> 01:17:24.270
exposing the vulnerability of
African Americans, Latinos,

01:17:24.270 --> 01:17:29.100
Native Americans, Jews
and immigrant communities.

01:17:29.100 --> 01:17:33.100
Their absent bodies stand
for their untold histories

01:17:33.100 --> 01:17:37.160
against the myth of a White
Anglo American identity.

01:17:37.160 --> 01:17:43.600
Titus Kafar paints
in the tradition

01:17:43.600 --> 01:17:46.490
of Euro American
Colonial portraiture,

01:17:46.490 --> 01:17:50.290
but then adds a contemporary
layer that is often physical,

01:17:50.290 --> 01:17:55.060
such as cutting, shrouding
or smearing the canvas.

01:17:55.060 --> 01:17:57.300
Before us we have a
well-known portrait

01:17:57.300 --> 01:18:01.600
of Thomas Jefferson shrouding
or revealing the portrait

01:18:01.600 --> 01:18:04.280
of an enslaved Black woman.

01:18:04.280 --> 01:18:07.400
In Kafar's words, "This
portrait is at once

01:18:07.400 --> 01:18:10.380
about Sally Mae Hemmings
and Thomas Jefferson,

01:18:10.380 --> 01:18:15.100
as well as the many woman who's
liberty was taken from them.

01:18:15.100 --> 01:18:18.060
And whose tragic
relationships have been shrouded

01:18:18.060 --> 01:18:21.330
by historically inaccurate
narratives of deified men

01:18:21.330 --> 01:18:24.290
in positions of power."

01:18:24.290 --> 01:18:28.690
The process of hiding the known
and revealing the unknown,

01:18:28.690 --> 01:18:32.600
according to co-curator
Osma Naim makes us realize

01:18:32.600 --> 01:18:34.700
that history is complex.

01:18:34.700 --> 01:18:36.000
It's messy.

01:18:36.000 --> 01:18:38.470
And filled with many
different perspectives,

01:18:38.470 --> 01:18:40.510
and that ultimately
our understanding

01:18:40.510 --> 01:18:43.170
of the past is more
complete when more

01:18:43.170 --> 01:18:46.110
of our stories can be told.

01:18:46.110 --> 01:18:50.330
Both Gonzalez Day and Kafar
use public domain works

01:18:50.330 --> 01:18:54.760
to probe foundational myths
in order to reclaim a space

01:18:54.760 --> 01:18:57.570
for those left unseen.

01:18:57.570 --> 01:19:02.450
I would encourage you to seek
out both their works not only

01:19:02.450 --> 01:19:06.220
as an illustration of the power
of using the public domain,

01:19:06.220 --> 01:19:09.220
but also to challenge
how each of us sees

01:19:09.220 --> 01:19:14.240
and understands our place
in the United States.

01:19:14.240 --> 01:19:17.740
Now, we are essentially
out of time for today.

